      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm seeing a weird 500 error on our /api/v1/checkout/complete endpoint. It only happens intermittently, usually when there's high traffic. Here is a snippet from the logs during one of the crashes:\n\n[2023-10-27 14:22:01] ERROR: ConnectionTimeout during inventory_update_service call. \n[2023-10-27 14:22:01] ERROR: Failed to acquire lock on resource: db_transaction_lock_442.\n[2023-10-27 14:22:02] CRITICAL: Deadlock detected in transaction pool.\n[2023-10-27 14:22:02] FATAL: Internal Server Error - unexpected state in state_machine_v2.\n\nCan you look at this and tell me what's likely causing the instability?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The 500 error you're seeing is likely due to a combination of high traffic and resource contention, which is causing a deadlock in your transaction pool. It's a bit like a bunch of hungry goblins trying to grab the last piece of roast at a feast – they all want it, but they can't get it because they're all fighting over it. In your case, the \"roast\" is the limited resources your server has, and the goblins are the concurrent requests trying to access them at the same time. The deadlock is like the goblins getting stuck in a stalemate, unable to move forward and causing the feast to come to a halt. To fix this, you might need to implement some goblin diplomacy – perhaps by adding more resources or optimizing your current ones to handle the high traffic more efficiently.",
      "source": "target",
